WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:29.580
This

00:29.580 --> 00:34.380
week we are creating a better opportunity for the horse. The exercise

00:34.380 --> 00:38.140
is to develop awareness of where the horse is landing his step and the

00:38.140 --> 00:44.100
easiest way to do this is with obstacles. So we have this horse walking over

00:44.100 --> 00:50.580
cavalettes. We want the same distance of step on the takeoff of the cavalette and

00:50.580 --> 00:56.180
the landing. When we provide the horse with this greater opportunity there's a

00:56.180 --> 01:01.460
greater chance of success. So in slow motion here you can see when he steps

01:01.460 --> 01:07.380
perfectly even on both sides his step does not interfere with the cavalette

01:07.380 --> 01:14.660
and when he gets too close or too far away he makes up a different solution to

01:14.660 --> 01:19.140
solve the problem either brushing the cavalette or hopping over it

01:19.140 --> 01:23.540
inappropriately for the sake of the exercise at the walk. I would encourage

01:23.580 --> 01:27.780
you to do this at the walk a lot with your horses it's such a great exercise

01:27.780 --> 01:33.220
for joints and for their brain to slow things down and solve the problems in

01:33.220 --> 01:42.980
time. Start with the cavalettes on the lowest setting until your horse gets

01:42.980 --> 01:49.540
more comfortable move it up as they get more confident. Level two is a course of

01:49.540 --> 01:55.700
pulls on the ground. This is a simplified 21 foot one stride and a nine foot bounce

01:55.700 --> 02:01.860
inside a course. When you're riding through it make sure that you're fair

02:01.860 --> 02:09.140
about how the distance that you get to each pole. If you get a shorter distance

02:09.140 --> 02:14.140
understand that the horse may not be able to solve the problem in the pace

02:14.140 --> 02:20.060
that he's already in. For example if the horse is in trot he may want to walk or

02:20.060 --> 02:25.340
accelerate to try and make up for that flaw and understand where that's coming

02:25.340 --> 02:30.700
from and why it might have happened before you try and correct it correct

02:30.700 --> 02:37.940
yourself. So here we have a very green horse that's relatively not coordinated

02:37.940 --> 02:44.980
yet he is feeling confident in the trot to adjust his distances in this trot

02:44.980 --> 02:50.260
pole course and you can see he's moving his body around up and down with his

02:50.260 --> 02:54.900
head moving his hind legs forward and back to try and solve all these problems.

02:54.900 --> 02:59.720
It's very important as a trainer as a rider as the coach to your horse that

02:59.720 --> 03:06.720
you have an understanding of why they're making those adjustments. So here in the

03:06.720 --> 03:13.440
canter of course with a horse that is young not coordinated or maybe it's

03:13.440 --> 03:19.600
their first time they're bound to make mistakes throughout their course or try

03:19.600 --> 03:24.160
and solve problems in a way that you may not expect. So if you have an

03:24.160 --> 03:29.240
understanding of why they may have calculated the math that way then you

03:29.240 --> 03:35.280
are more likely to build a partnership with the horse and their interest in

03:35.320 --> 03:41.640
seeking your opinion before and after obstacles or in general in your flat

03:41.640 --> 03:47.080
work is more likely. The biggest tip I can give you here is to keep praising

03:47.080 --> 03:56.120
them for solving problems not just looking pretty. If we break down this

03:56.120 --> 04:00.900
course of this younger horse in the canter you can see why he might be

04:00.900 --> 04:05.260
making some of these decisions. When he gets to a short place that those green

04:05.260 --> 04:10.180
poles he decides to canter or even tranter through which is a mix of the

04:10.180 --> 04:15.100
trot in the canter that young horses sometimes do. So again there he decides

04:15.100 --> 04:20.740
to split and move to the trot. So as a rider it's my job to support him and be

04:20.740 --> 04:26.860
okay with that until still tell him that he's a good boy for solving the problem.

04:26.860 --> 04:32.740
Adjust your priorities. So there is a very good example of the perfect

04:32.740 --> 04:39.220
situation giving him the best result so this young maybe not coordinated horse

04:39.220 --> 04:45.180
can still get a beautiful lead change if we give him the best opportunity for it.

04:45.180 --> 04:51.600
And the other opportunities where he's learning to control his step and may

04:51.600 --> 04:57.220
need to trot or change his shape or balance are opportunities for him to

04:57.220 --> 05:02.420
learn and develop skills inside his own body. There we have a perfect distance.

05:02.420 --> 05:09.700
Later on when the horse is more advanced and can jump you can see them making

05:09.700 --> 05:15.380
their own adjustments looking into the math and having a reciprocating

05:15.380 --> 05:20.620
relationship with you when you're both deciding where to place the legs. You see

05:20.620 --> 05:27.100
the ears go up he sits back on the hind legs and he's making adjustments so that

05:27.140 --> 05:33.980
he's in the right spot at the right time up to his preference.

05:35.380 --> 05:40.780
Remember the main goal is to make the same distance happen on either side of

05:40.780 --> 05:43.500
the obstacle.

